        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>1</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>5 Triangle <add>?</add></placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <date>28 Nov-/44-</date>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Sir-</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Being very much<lb/> engaged in writing, my dear<lb/> Father has
                kindly promised<lb/> to write to you on all business<lb/> matters for me, which
                letter<lb/> will go by the next steamer<lb/> I am writing this to<lb/> accompany the
                books, in<lb/> case they should arrive<lb/> before my Father's letter.<lb/> They
                will go thro' <persName>Mr Staker</persName><lb/> of the
                    <placeName>Strand</placeName>, but as it is<lb/> a <del>very</del> large
                parcel—we have<lb/> offered to pay part of the<lb/> freight, which proportion</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>2</p>
            <p><persName>Mr Staker</persName> thinks had better<lb/> be paid to <persName>Messrs C.
                    I Hart</persName><lb/> in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>, which I
                shall<lb/> feel obliged by your doing<lb/> &amp; deducting the said sum<lb/> from
                the proceeds of the books<lb/> I am hourly in expectation<lb/> of my 7<hi rend="sup"
                    >th</hi> number, my<lb/> printer having promised it<lb/> me to day. Should it
                leave<lb/> in time, I shall send it<lb/> with the other &amp; not trouble<lb/>
                <persName>Mr Longman</persName> until <date>January</date>.<lb/> I have put up <hi
                    rend="underline">30</hi> copies<lb/> of each number—2.3.4—<lb/> singly &amp; 5
                &amp; 6 together, as they<lb/> now published and <hi rend="underline">5</hi>
                addition<lb/> at copies of the number one<lb/> to make up the 30 &amp; 25
                    having<add>?</add></p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">3</p>
            <p>been sent to you originally<lb/> you will therefore in this<lb/> parcel find <hi
                    rend="underline">125 books</hi>, that<lb/> is if the number 7 does<lb/> not come
                in time. If it<lb/> should, you will find <hi rend="underline">155</hi><lb/> instead
                of the 125 &amp; the<lb/> others. I hope to send monthly.<lb/>
                <persName>Mr Cohen</persName> of <placeName>Savannah</placeName><lb/> has kindly
                offered to be my<lb/> agent for 50 copies of each<lb/> number therefore I would<lb/>
                rather wait to see if those<lb/> sell before sending a larger<lb/> number than 30 to
                you. You<lb/> will also find in the parcel<lb/> a complete set of the numbers<lb/>
                as far as they are out,<lb/> which you will oblige me<lb/> by presenting in my
                name</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>4</p>
            <p>&amp; with my compts to <persName>Mr<lb/> Chandler</persName>, the gentleman who<lb/>
                reviewed my “Spirit” &amp; the continu<lb/>ation of the Nos. for yourself, as Editor
                of the Oc.<lb/> I thank you much for your<lb/> kind exertions in the disposal<lb/>
                of my books &amp; you will oblige<lb/> me greatly by saying the same<lb/> to
                    <persName>Mr Hart</persName>. I thank you<lb/> also for your letter &amp; your
                advice<lb/> concerning the alteration in<lb/> my style of writing &amp;
                thinking<lb/> kindly meant, but impossible<lb/> either thro' conviction, or
                inclination<lb/> to be followed. Harshness has<lb/> never yet done good. Our
                God<lb/> is Love &amp; so is His Law, (as<lb/> the Bible gives it, not as it<lb/>
                has often been perverted by<lb/> mistaken zealots) &amp; I am content<lb/> to follow
                the same blessed<lb/> course. I do not quite know<lb/> how you could have
                    lead<add>?</add><lb/> the <persName>Perry<add>?</add></persName> Family to
                assert</p>
            <pb n="5"/>
            <p>5</p>
            <p>that <persName>Reuben</persName> is led to<lb/> return to his faith, thro'<lb/> the
                kindness of his Mother<lb/> &amp; <persName>Sarah Levison</persName>. A more<lb/>
                careful reading would convince<lb/> you, that it was <hi rend="underline"
                    >affliction</hi><lb/> &amp; the <hi rend="underline">study of both
                    religions</hi><lb/> which saved him, from<lb/>
                <sic>apostacy</sic>, &amp; caused him to<lb/> return. <hi rend="underline">I</hi>
                feel imagi=<lb/>nation a gift from God, and<lb/> as such to be used—not checked<lb/>
                Believe me, there are many<lb/> hearts &amp; dispositions which are<lb/> far more
                likely to be guided<lb/> by Imagination, than by a<lb/> direct reproof. How did<lb/>
                <persName>Nathan</persName> reprove <persName>David</persName>, was<lb/> it not by
                affecting his<lb/> heart &amp; imagination, &amp; causing</p>
            <pb n="6"/>
            <p>6</p>
            <p>him in fact to condemn<lb/> himself. I do not ask<lb/> your <hi rend="underline"
                    >praise</hi> as a reviewer<lb/> but your <hi rend="underline">justice</hi>,
                which in<lb/> your first notice of my<lb/> Records of <placeName>Israel</placeName>
                you did not<lb/> do me. Your second notice<lb/> is very different. The great<lb/>
                mistake of all the Editors of<lb/> Jewish magazines, is that<lb/> the office of
                reviewer is an<lb/> easy one, &amp; requires neither<lb/> much time, nor much
                talent<lb/> when it so imperatively <add>?</add><lb/> both, that in all English<lb/>
                magazines &amp; papers—Reviewers<lb/> are a distinct branch of<lb/> literary men
                &amp; their articles<lb/> of such importance, and<lb/> considered to require
                such</p>
            <pb n="7"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">7</p>
            <p>talent, as to be paid better<lb/> than for any thing else.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">You must pardon one<lb/> observation only written<lb/> because, I
                once praised<lb/> your magazine, for a quality<lb/> which I really grieve to
                see<lb/> that it no longer possesses.<lb/> I mean liberality and<lb/> impartiality.
                You may<lb/> differ with your correspondents<lb/> &amp; of course as an Editor
                have<lb/> the privilege of writing what<lb/> you please, but it is with<lb/> real
                regret I perceive the<lb/> very different spirit breathing<add>?</add><lb/> in your
                later numbers to<lb/> the mild toleration pervading<lb/> your first. Perhaps
                this<lb/> observation is uncalled for.</p>
            <pb n="8"/>
            <p>8</p>
            <p>but you must pardon it<lb/> when I feel that loving kindness, and<lb/>
                    forbearance<add>?</add> are so very much<lb/> needed, it must be a source<lb/>
                of pain, to see those who<lb/> might forward the cause of love<lb/> rather retarding
                than advancing<lb/> it. Of such subjects we<lb/> can never think alike &amp;<lb/>
                therefore perhaps I am wrong<lb/> to write of them—but I wish<lb/> you to know my
                sentiments<lb/> on the subject that you may<lb/> perceive how impossible it<lb/> is
                for my writings ever to<lb/> arrive at the standard you<lb/> require. I have
                written<lb/> much more at length than<lb/> I intended, &amp; must therefore<lb/>
                conclude with my Parents<lb/> regards I am dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <persName role="author">Grace Aquilar</persName>
            </p>
